The fix: add a check after inferTemplateTypesFromParameters to return false if the inferred map is empty.

But careful: The original code already checks keys.isEmpty() and returns false. If keys is not empty but inferred is empty, then the replacer will do nothing, and madeChanges will be false, so the return value is false anyway. However, the visit and type setting still happens. If the visit causes a problem (e.g., due to null), then we want to skip it. So adding a check for inferred.isEmpty() early might prevent that.

Also, the bug might be that the visit changes the function type incorrectly even when inferred is empty. So early return is safe.

Thus, the fix:

```
private boolean inferTemplatedTypesForCall(
    Node n, FunctionType fnType) {
  final ImmutableList<TemplateType> keys = fnType.getTemplateTypeMap()
      .getTemplateKeys();
  if (keys.isEmpty()) {
    return false;
  }

  // Try to infer the template types
  Map<TemplateType, JSType> inferred = 
      inferTemplateTypesFromParameters(fnType, n);

  if (inferred.isEmpty()) {
    return false;
  }

  // Replace all template types...
  TemplateTypeReplacer replacer = new TemplateTypeReplacer(
      registry, inferred);
  Node callTarget = n.getFirstChild();

  FunctionType replacementFnType = fnType.visit(replacer)
      .toMaybeFunctionType();
  Preconditions.checkNotNull(replacementFnType);

  callTarget.setJSType(replacementFnType);
  n.setJSType(replacementFnType.getReturnType());

  return replacer.madeChanges;
}
```

